---

<DocLayout
  title="deleteByDrag"
  description="How deleteByDrag inputType handles content deletion via drag operations and varies across browsers."
  currentPath={Astro.url.pathname}
>
        <DocSection title="Overview">
          <p class="m-0 mb-4">
            The <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[0.85em]">deleteByDrag</code> inputType is triggered when content is deleted by dragging it out of a contenteditable element (typically to a non-editable area or external application). The browser removes the dragged content from the DOM.
          </p>
        </DocSection>

        <DocSection title="Basic Behavior">
          <DocInfoBox title="Scenario: Text dragged out of contenteditable">
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div>
                <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold mb-2 text-text-primary">Before (Text selected)</h4>
                <div class="bg-bg-surface border border-border-light rounded-md p-3 font-mono text-sm">
                  <div class="text-text-secondary">HTML:</div>
                  <div class="text-text-primary mt-1">&lt;p&gt;Hello <span class="bg-yellow-200 dark:bg-yellow-900/40">world</span> text&lt;/p&gt;</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              
              <div>
                <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold mb-2 text-text-primary">After dragging "world" outside contenteditable</h4>
                <div class="bg-bg-surface border border-border-light rounded-md p-3 font-mono text-sm">
                  <div class="text-text-secondary">HTML:</div>
                  <div class="text-text-primary mt-1">&lt;p&gt;Hello <span class="bg-blue-200 dark:bg-blue-900/40 px-1 rounded">|</span> text&lt;/p&gt;</div>
                  <div class="text-text-secondary mt-2 text-xs">Dragged content removed from DOM</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </DocInfoBox>
        </DocSection>

        <DocSection title="Browser Support">
          <DocAlert type="info" title="ℹ️ Limited Browser Support">
            <p class="m-0 mb-2 text-sm">
              <code class="bg-white/50 dark:bg-black/20 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[0.85em]">deleteByDrag</code> is not widely supported across all browsers. Some browsers may use <code class="bg-white/50 dark:bg-black/20 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[0.85em]">deleteContent</code> or other inputType values instead.
            </p>
            <p class="m-0 text-sm">
              Always test drag-and-drop deletion behavior across different browsers and platforms.
            </p>
          </DocAlert>
        </DocSection>

        <DocSection title="Difference from deleteContent">
          <DocInfoBox>
            <div class="space-y-3 text-sm">
              <div>
                <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2 text-text-primary">deleteByDrag</h4>
                <ul class="m-0 pl-6 text-text-secondary">
                  <li class="mb-1">Content is deleted by dragging it out of the element</li>
                  <li class="mb-1">Requires drag-and-drop interaction</li>
                  <li class="mb-1">May be used when dragging to external applications</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              
              <div>
                <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2 text-text-primary">deleteContent</h4>
                <ul class="m-0 pl-6 text-text-secondary">
                  <li class="mb-1">Content is deleted via keyboard (Delete key) or programmatically</li>
                  <li class="mb-1">No drag interaction required</li>
                  <li class="mb-1">More commonly used inputType</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </DocInfoBox>
        </DocSection>

        <DocSection title="Editor-Specific Handling">
          <p class="m-0 mb-4">
            Different editor frameworks handle drag deletion similarly to regular deletion. Here's how major editors implement deleteByDrag:
          </p>

          <EditorExample
            editor="slate"
            title="Drag Deletion Handling"
            description="Slate handles drag deletion through drag events:"
            code={`import { Editor, Transforms } from 'slate';

element.addEventListener('beforeinput', (e) => {
  if (e.inputType === 'deleteByDrag') {
    e.preventDefault();
    
    const { selection } = editor;
    if (selection && !selection.isCollapsed) {
      // Delete selected content
      Transforms.delete(editor);
    }
  }
});

// Also handle dragend event
element.addEventListener('dragend', (e) => {
  // Content has been dragged out
  // Selection may need to be updated
});`}
            features={[
              '<strong>Transforms.delete:</strong> Uses same deletion method as regular delete operations.',
              '<strong>Drag event handling:</strong> May need to handle <code class="bg-bg-surface px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-[0.85em]">dragend</code> event separately.',
            ]}
          />

          <EditorExample
            editor="prosemirror"
            title="Drag Deletion Handling"
            description="ProseMirror handles drag deletion:"
            code={`import { deleteSelection } from 'prosemirror-commands';

view.dom.addEventListener('beforeinput', (e) => {
  if (e.inputType === 'deleteByDrag') {
    e.preventDefault();
    const { state, dispatch } = view;
    
    if (!state.selection.empty) {
      if (deleteSelection(state, dispatch)) {
        // Handled
      }
    }
  }
});`}
            features={[
              '<strong>deleteSelection command:</strong> Uses same deletion command as regular delete operations.',
              '<strong>Selection handling:</strong> Requires non-empty selection.',
            ]}
          />

          <EditorExample
            editor="draftjs"
            title="Drag Deletion Handling"
            description="Draft.js handles drag deletion:"
            code={`import { EditorState, Modifier } from 'draft-js';

function handleDragDeletion(editorState) {
  const contentState = editorState.getCurrentContent();
  const selection = editorState.getSelection();
  
  if (!selection.isCollapsed) {
    // Delete selected content
    const newContentState = Modifier.removeRange(
      contentState,
      selection,
      'forward'
    );
    
    return EditorState.push(
      editorState,
      newContentState,
      'remove-range'
    );
  }
  
  return editorState;
}`}
            features={[
              '<strong>Modifier.removeRange:</strong> Uses same deletion method as regular delete operations.',
              '<strong>Selection required:</strong> Requires non-empty selection.',
            ]}
          />
        </DocSection>

